4 SYNOPSIS:
5 Under existing law, deductions may be made from
6 the salary of state employees for membership dues,
7 voluntary contributions, and insurance premiums.
8 Existing law also provides a 10-day window for
9 education employees to stop payroll deductions for
10 membership dues.
11 This bill would prohibit membership dues for
12 labor organizations from being deducted from the salary
13 of certain education employees.
14 This bill would require employee organizations
15 and professional associations to allow all state
16 employees to revoke their membership at any time and
17 without reason, and would prohibit those organizations
18 and associations from limiting an employee's ability to
19 revoke his or her membership.
20 This bill would require state employees who
21 revoke their membership from an employee organization
22 or professional association to immediately be released
23 from obligations relating to membership dues or
24 voluntary contributions and be removed from the
25 organization or association's membership list.
26 This bill would also remove statutory
27 limitations on when a state employee may opt out of
28 salary deductions for membership dues or voluntary
Page 1

salary deductions for membership dues or voluntary
HB666 INTRODUCED
29 contributions, and would provide that employees must be
30 allowed to cancel those deductions at any time.
31
